'''Marine forensics''' refers to the scientific study of incidents or accidents occurring as a result of or involving bodies of water including [[ocean]]s, [[stream]]s or [[river]]s, [[lake]]s or [[pond]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sname.org/forensics2012/whatismarineforensics/ |title=What is Marine Forensics? |work=International Marine Forensics Symposium 2012 web site |accessdate=3 April 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110821053655/http://www.sname.org/forensics2012/whatismarineforensics/ |archivedate=21 August 2011 |df= }}</ref> This science borrows techniques from traditional terrestrial [[forensic science]] and blends them with technologies and methods adapted for underwater [[research]].
One of the most well-known marine forensics programs is [[the NOS Marine Forensics Program]], which was founded in the 1970s and is the only laboratory in the U.S. dedicated to the forensic analysis of [[marine biology|marine species]].

